great video!! really appreciate the tips 

i'm more cautious with the --dangerously-skip-permissions at least when i'm working on stuff that's live in production. just earlier claude suggested to push some untested debugging code to prod, just because the dev server wasn't running!!  

it was like "hm, dev server isn't running, let's just push to prod, so it'll deploy - what's the worst that could happen?"  like, you okay homie? I know AI is coming for my job, but didn't know it's doing that by trying to get me fired lol. 

if you want to use those yolo features you always have to check if they are worth the risk. think about what would happen if you would break prod, or drop a prod table or some other dev nightmare. if you're working on your 26th to-do app side project, where you will be the only user ever, then that's fine, just don't do it on a live project with users, where a fuckup like that can have consequences which are not worth the risk. 

other than that, my experience with claude code has been nothing but incredible!

comments.text:
Man, to be honest, Im in the exact same situation. Im a ChatGPT Plus user, and lately Ive been working on some Java projects that require more context. But ChatGPT often gets confused, generates insecure or incorrect code, and sometimes tries to guess usages or parameter types that dont exist. I even tried switching to other 4o versions like o3 or o4-mini-high, but honestly, those were even worse. They hallucinate way too fast, generating completely different  and often wrong  code. Its been really frustrating.

One day while browsing online, I saw someone say Claude was way better than ChatGPT, so I decided to give it a try. I was blown away by the results  even just using the free version. The code it produced felt safer, had proper error handling, and was written with much more care. The next day, I wanted to clean up and modularize my code, and asked Claude to help organize my project structure. It gave me all the files and folder structures I needed  basically a full code refactor. I was genuinely impressed. And Ive been using ChatGPT for almost a year now, but Ive never seen anything like that from it.

That said, Im still a little hesitant because I saw a lot of users complain about Claudes limits. From what Ive gathered, the Opus plan gets limited really fast, but the Sonnet plan seems more stable. If Im not mistaken, its something like 45 prompts every 5 hours  which honestly sounds fair, gives you time to think and take breaks. Im seriously thinking of canceling ChatGPT and switching to Claude next month.

If youve already subscribed to Claude and had a good or bad experience, could you share it with me?

Thanks! :)

comments.text:
It is possible to give some default permissions to claude code, while denying it some commands. You need to create a file called "settings.local.json" under "./claude" at the root folder and put the permissions. You can ask claude code to create this file and configure it for you. For instance, these are mine:

{
  "permissions": {
    "allow": [
      "Bash",
      "mcp__ide__executeCode",
      "WebFetch",
      "WebSearch",
      "Bash(npx:*)",
      "mcp__context7__resolve-library-id",
      "mcp__context7__get-library-docs",
      "Read",
      "Write",
      "Edit",
      "MultiEdit",
      "LS",
      "Glob",
      "Grep",
      "Task",
      "TodoWrite",
      "TodoRead",
      "NotebookRead",
      "NotebookEdit",
      "exit_plan_mode",
      "mcp__ide__getDiagnostics",
      "Agent"
    ],
    "deny": ["Bash(npm:*)", "Bash(npm *)"],
    "requestApproval": [
      "Bash(git commit*)",
      "Bash(git push*)",
      "Bash(ggprod*)",
      "Bash(ggpush*)",
      "Bash(ggmerge*)"
    ]
  }
}

Since I have this file, it is now always on autopilot, and always uses pnpm since npm is restricted. If it was to commit or push it needs to request permission explicitely from me.

comments.text:
I've used Cursor and Claude Code in parallel and compared them - even thinking sonnet model in Cursor writes s**t compared to Claude Code. Claude code rewrites code after Cursor much better than Cursor after Claude code. I had a chance to compare them because at first I started with Cursor and I liked it for the first time. But it was my first impression. It ended up when I reached my usage limits in 7 days for Pro subscription. Then I paid 60$ for Cursor Pro+ for "triple more limits" in hope that it will be enough for me to use it at least for 3 weeks, but I again reached limits in 6-7 days and now it asks me to either turn on pay as you go or buy more expensive subscription than pro+. Their policy of hiding user's statistics of usage and missing ability to see actual limits is frustrating. 
In Claude code I love how I can operate with current context window with ability to do custom compact logic, instead of having laggy and freezing Cursor IDE just in the middle of my large complex task and you are forced either restart IDE and start new chat to get rid of lags or you must accept it and wait for 5-10 seconds freezes for each chat window interaction. So my subscription for Cursor Pro+ is still active and since it's "burst" limit is reached and I have ability to use it only 1-2 hours a day I decided to find alternative and there is how I found Claude Code. Now I have simple Pro subscription for Claude with their "5 hours sessions" limited to some boundaries. When I don't think about usage I can reach session limit in about 2 hours(it is 6-8 hours of full unlimited sessions a day). But with ability to monitor my usage and using it in a smart way with thoughtful planning I am able to fit my needs and distribute evenly my usage in this 5 hour session. And quality of code in much greater and while I have Cursor subscription active I can use it's daily limit to write first iteration of the code, and after this fix and debug it with Claude help.
